My To Do list was 35 pages. It contained a lot of notes about newsletter topics and blurbs, hashtags to add to Instagram posts. When I deleted all the writing stuff, I was left with four bullet points.

'Round here... I got lots of time.

full_text: @PJConnollyMD That's a good point. I got to have a taste of it. What I could have done with my time and my energy if the right doors were open and if the snowball had started rolling in the other direction. Now it's taking up about 60 pounds of space in the recycling bin.

@LRyan_Storms And we need to stop telling writers that their experiences can hold them back. If facing hardship and talking about it exclude you from future endeavor, then it's the system that's the problem - not the transparency.

Now back to the process of learning not to be who I am.

@kpanyc If anyone skimming this threads wants to read another thread on what the end of an author's side hustle looks like... here you go. 26 years. Hundreds of rejections. 7 books. One award. And a whole lot of pain and struggle and crickets.

https://t.co/RvkCmDohRc
full_text(utf-8): b"@kpanyc If anyone skimming this threads wants to read another thread on what the end of an author's side hustle looks like... here you go. 26 years. Hundreds of rejections. 7 books. One award. And a whole lot of pain and struggle and crickets.\n\nhttps://t.co/RvkCmDohRc"

full_text: @PJConnollyMD One book. One book did that. The rest achieved angry readers and a lot of pain on my part. Thousands of dollars I'll never get back. The $ aside... Shrug. Anyone can throw 80k words in a line and put it on paper. Selling it is the goal. And I can't get there.
full_text(utf-8): b"@PJConnollyMD One book. One book did that. The rest achieved angry readers and a lot of pain on my part. Thousands of dollars I'll never get back. The $ aside... Shrug. Anyone can throw 80k words in a line and put it on paper. Selling it is the goal. And I can't get there."

full_text: @kpanyc I believe that's true. I don't have what it takes to endure 26 years of sometimes rather rude rejections from agents. Vanity publishers aren't the answer. Instead, I tried. But it's painful not to reach the goal post. My only choice is b/w paths of unfulfilled purpose.
full_text(utf-8): b"@kpanyc I believe that's true. I don't have what it takes to endure 26 years of sometimes rather rude rejections from agents. Vanity publishers aren't the answer. Instead, I tried. But it's painful not to reach the goal post. My only choice is b/w paths of unfulfilled purpose."

full_text:
@kpanyc You have no idea how much this means to me today.

After 26 yrs of trying & failing, all I am is a failure. Trad pub is out of reach, so I self pub. I'm a full time marketer & hate my career. With support, my 7 books might sell. Instead, it's crickets. I threw in the towel today.

full_text: But there's a worse hunger in deciding the horizon is no longer the destination. Out in the desert, the horizon is all there is. You either keep walking or sit still. And there are creatures in the night, hungry creatures that pick you off unless you're running. You trudge on.
full_text(utf-8): b"But there's a worse hunger in deciding the horizon is no longer the destination. Out in the desert, the horizon is all there is. You either keep walking or sit still. And there are creatures in the night, hungry creatures that pick you off unless you're running. You trudge on."

full_text: It strips you bare, takes your food, deprives you of water. It's priceless in the costly way, because it chips away at your soul until there's no meat left to feed the birds of prey.
full_text(utf-8): b"It strips you bare, takes your food, deprives you of water. It's priceless in the costly way, because it chips away at your soul until there's no meat left to feed the birds of prey."

full_text: Every time you check the meter, you find the distance is immeasurable. The cost of spanning that distance is *priceless. Those who reach the horizon define *priceless as a 15 minute stroll. They hardly broke a sweat. But for those in the desert, priceless is a costly thing.
full_text(utf-8): b'Every time you check the meter, you find the distance is immeasurable. The cost of spanning that distance is *priceless. Those who reach the horizon define *priceless as a 15 minute stroll. They hardly broke a sweat. But for those in the desert, priceless is a costly thing.'

full_text: If it's true that you can't reach the horizon unless you want it bad enough, not reaching it no matter how far you walk must mean you didn't want it enough. The remaining distance of want is calculated in degrees of more.

full_text:
Hi. My name is Penny. I'm a lawyer. I file briefs really good. You can pay me $20k a day to represent you.

full_text: @jgownder We don't all have the same anthropological glue. It's hard enough to convince people in rural Maine to foot the bill for rebuilding New Orleans after the 5th destructive hurricane. Maine needs more road work every year (ice, snow) than Phoenix. Community gov reduces division.
full_text(utf-8): b"@jgownder We don't all have the same anthropological glue. It's hard enough to convince people in rural Maine to foot the bill for rebuilding New Orleans after the 5th destructive hurricane. Maine needs more road work every year (ice, snow) than Phoenix. Community gov reduces division."

full_text: @jgownder Absolutely. That's why we have federal laws & EPA regs. I don't think that all laws are cookie cutter. I was just without water for 3 days because of aging infrastructure. My PA sewer bill reflects those challenges. But a shiny new town in CO isn't motivated 2 pay for my needs.
full_text(utf-8): b"@jgownder Absolutely. That's why we have federal laws & EPA regs. I don't think that all laws are cookie cutter. I was just without water for 3 days because of aging infrastructure. My PA sewer bill reflects those challenges. But a shiny new town in CO isn't motivated 2 pay for my needs."

full_text: @jgownder My view: That's a recipe for disaster. Humans are animals. We're designed to live in packs of about 125 where we create rules and systems for adherence. There are norms in smaller systems that motivate us to stay together. Too big, we bicker and fail w/o consequences.
full_text(utf-8): b"@jgownder My view: That's a recipe for disaster. Humans are animals. We're designed to live in packs of about 125 where we create rules and systems for adherence. I VOTED!

1. Fill out ballot.
2. Put in security envelope.
3. Put in outer envelope. Sign. date.
4. Drive to box.
5. Say hi to attendant.

Kudos to the elderly woman behind me who yelled HELL YES DEMOCRACY.

full_text:
@GuerillaMemoir For me - I either have to write mass-market shrill OR I have to be okay with fewer sales. I prefer the latter, even if it's hard.

I hate movies. There are only three plots & they're all overdone. I'd rather wander off into the woods & call it quits than write what I don't like.
full_text(utf-8): b"@GuerillaMemoir For me - I either have to write mass-market shrill OR I have to be okay with fewer sales. I prefer the latter, even if it's hard.\n\nI hate movies. There are only three plots & they're all overdone. I'd rather wander off into the woods & call it quits than write what I don't like."

full_text:
@GuerillaMemoir It's hard. It may be tempting to throw "romance!" into the marketing, but if it isn't true, it generates bad reviews. And writing something you don't like won't create a good book.

The trick is to be okay with writing what you love. And it's okay to admit when that's hard.

full_text:
So what are the limitations? I don't write erotica or mysteries with bombs and guns.

I write character-driven fiction set in small towns. Cozy small town fiction. It's not a genre. It's impossible to find readers.

And I just don't know where the breaking point is.
